WEBVTT

00:09.801 --> 00:19.811
♪

00:20.061 --> 00:30.071
♪

00:32.156 --> 00:34.993
And with the industrialrevolution came millionaires

00:35.034 --> 00:38.246
who'd compete to throwthe most lavish parties

00:38.246 --> 00:39.581
and they'd try to out-doone another

00:39.581 --> 00:43.543
with their big dessertsor their huge hats.

00:43.585 --> 00:45.086
They'd even compete to see

00:45.128 --> 00:47.422
who could have the mostmagnificent mansions.

00:47.422 --> 00:54.262
One man plated his entirebathtub in 24-karat gold leaf.

00:54.262 --> 00:57.057
Imagine taking a bubble bathin that.

00:57.098 --> 00:59.267
But miss, aren't placeslike that

00:59.309 --> 01:00.769
just in fairy tales?

01:00.810 --> 01:02.437
Oh, no.

01:02.479 --> 01:04.605
No, they're very real.Trust me.

01:04.605 --> 01:07.650
In fact, I used to spendmy summers in a big mansion

01:07.692 --> 01:09.736
just like thatwhen I was your age.

01:09.778 --> 01:11.696
Well, back in the States.

01:11.738 --> 01:13.239
Lucy?

01:14.449 --> 01:16.242
Oh, excuse me. Excuse me.

01:16.284 --> 01:18.161
Enjoy the rest of your tour.

01:20.288 --> 01:23.374
Lucy, giving children toursin the galleries again?

01:23.416 --> 01:25.710
That's what our docentsare for.

01:25.752 --> 01:26.753
Sorry, Isabelle.

01:27.045 --> 01:30.173
I was just passing throughand I guess I got pulled in.

01:30.215 --> 01:31.633
I love that exhibit.

01:31.674 --> 01:32.967
Come along.

01:32.967 --> 01:34.594
I need my director ofdevelopment upstairs.

01:34.636 --> 01:36.971
We've got to plan forthe fundraiser tonight.

01:37.013 --> 01:38.306
So catch me up where we are.

01:38.306 --> 01:39.641
Sure.

01:39.682 --> 01:41.267
So I re-workedthe seating chart.

01:41.309 --> 01:43.186
All of our major donorswill be sitting up front,

01:43.228 --> 01:46.397
and you will be between the LordMayor and Ambassador Philips.

01:46.439 --> 01:49.442
Oh, Lucy. You remind me of me.

01:49.484 --> 01:52.111
Museum directors aren't made,they're born.

01:52.153 --> 01:55.406
And you truly have the makingsof one of the greats.

01:55.448 --> 02:00.161
You know, I'm relocating backto New York soon.

02:00.203 --> 02:02.247
I can't think of anyonewho works harder than you.

02:02.288 --> 02:03.957
Thank you.

02:03.998 --> 02:06.334
Your passion and knowledgeof history is undeniable.

02:06.334 --> 02:09.586
Your organizational skillsare top-notch.

02:09.628 --> 02:13.341
Well, I've decided to nominateyou as my replacement

02:13.383 --> 02:15.552
when I retire next month.

02:15.593 --> 02:18.555
Isabelle. Really?

02:18.596 --> 02:20.932
Oh my gosh, that would bea dream come true.

02:20.974 --> 02:24.060
But before we pop the champagne,just one more hurdle.

02:24.102 --> 02:27.355
I do need to get the trusteeson board with you first.

02:27.355 --> 02:30.525
I will wear them down like...

02:30.567 --> 02:33.486
Like... like the Dukeof Wellington wore down Napoleon

02:33.528 --> 02:34.737
at Waterloo.

02:34.779 --> 02:35.864
Precisely.

02:39.993 --> 02:42.453
[laughs]

02:47.041 --> 02:50.253
Ok. Name tags done,catering taken care of,

02:50.295 --> 02:53.590
Isabelle's speech printedand proofed.

02:53.631 --> 02:56.509
I don't think Hannibal had thismuch to do crossing the Alps.

02:56.551 --> 02:57.510
[laughs]

02:57.552 --> 02:59.387
Anything else, Josephine?

02:59.429 --> 03:01.264
Uh, that just about does it.

03:01.306 --> 03:03.308
I'd say we're ready forthe fundraiser tonight.

03:03.349 --> 03:07.103
Well then, since the newexhibit's going in downstairs,

03:07.145 --> 03:10.690
I might just sneak downfor an early peek.

03:10.732 --> 03:13.193
Boss, you're meeting the HobartFoundation at 2:00

03:13.234 --> 03:16.404
and then Lady Jacobs to naildown her gift for the east wing,

03:16.404 --> 03:18.740
and you still have to call backthat cute Cambridge professor

03:18.740 --> 03:21.159
that wants to take you outon a date.

03:21.200 --> 03:23.036
He didn't want to take meout on a date.

03:23.077 --> 03:25.663
He just wants my help writinghis grant proposal.

03:25.705 --> 03:28.583
Lucy, you're a victimof your own success.

03:28.625 --> 03:30.752
Well, I should take these downto the archives.

03:30.752 --> 03:31.544
Oh!

03:32.754 --> 03:33.755
I got it.

03:33.796 --> 03:38.259
And, uh, cover for meif anyone asks?

03:38.259 --> 03:39.886
Have fun.

03:39.928 --> 03:42.513
Enjoy the new exhibit.

03:55.985 --> 03:58.863
Oops, sorry.

04:18.548 --> 04:19.634
Thank you.

04:33.022 --> 04:34.315
Excuse me, sir.

04:34.315 --> 04:35.692
Is this rubbishyou're throwing out?

04:35.733 --> 04:37.485
Hey. That I am, why?

04:37.485 --> 04:39.862
This pot right here is actuallyDelft pottery.

04:39.904 --> 04:41.489
It's a real treasure.

04:41.489 --> 04:43.283
You might wanna hang on to it.

04:43.324 --> 04:45.952
I had no idea.Thank you.

04:45.994 --> 04:46.995
You're welcome.

04:47.036 --> 04:48.955
Take good care of it.

04:51.666 --> 04:52.583
Hi, Nigel.

04:52.625 --> 04:53.668
Did you have a good day?

04:53.710 --> 04:54.711
Great, Lucy.

04:54.752 --> 04:55.878
Oh, this came for you.

04:55.920 --> 04:56.838
Special delivery.

04:57.088 --> 04:59.257
All the way from the U. S. of A.Looks official.

04:59.298 --> 05:02.010
H.K. Rourke,Attorney at Law.

05:08.516 --> 05:09.851
"Lucy Windsor, I've been tryingto reach you

05:09.892 --> 05:11.853
"since your great aunt...

05:16.691 --> 05:18.776
This can't be.

05:26.701 --> 05:28.578
[knocking]

05:29.871 --> 05:33.249
Lucy, I'm so sorry to hearabout your aunt.

05:33.291 --> 05:34.375
Thanks, Isabelle.

05:34.417 --> 05:36.878
She was a wonderful lady.

05:36.878 --> 05:39.088
She passed away last month.

05:39.130 --> 05:40.798
Oh, is that her?

05:40.840 --> 05:43.885
Yes. Aunt Grace.

05:43.926 --> 05:49.348
The kindest, most adventuroussoul you could ever meet.

05:49.390 --> 05:53.227
Wow, what a lovely estate.

05:53.269 --> 05:55.772
I'd guess Gilded Age Era.

05:55.813 --> 05:56.773
Upstate New York?

05:57.065 --> 05:59.901
Close, Rhode Island.It's called Wycliffe House.

05:59.942 --> 06:02.028
I grew up spendingmy summers there.

06:02.070 --> 06:03.488
Your Aunt lived there.

06:03.529 --> 06:04.822
Great Aunt, actually.

06:04.864 --> 06:06.908
Her husband Arthur wasthe last of the Wycliff's.

06:06.949 --> 06:10.661
His grandfather Henry builtthe house over 100 years ago.

06:10.703 --> 06:14.082
I spoke to my folks and theysaid that Arthur didn't have

06:14.082 --> 06:15.917
any remaining family

06:15.958 --> 06:20.630
so Aunt Grace bequeathedthe whole thing to me.

06:20.671 --> 06:22.298
Inheriting a mansion?

06:22.340 --> 06:24.842
That's something that doesn'thappen every day.

06:24.884 --> 06:28.805
Aunt Grace invited us up thereevery single summer

06:28.846 --> 06:31.474
until I headed off to Oxford.

06:32.809 --> 06:35.686
Now who's that?

06:35.728 --> 06:38.856
Uh, Duncan.

06:38.898 --> 06:41.275
Son of the caretakers.

06:41.275 --> 06:45.029
My aunt took him inafter he lost his parents.

06:45.071 --> 06:46.823
Uh, anyway-

06:46.864 --> 06:48.616
Oh, Lucy, I hate to ask,

06:48.616 --> 06:51.953
but must you go all the wayto the States right now?

06:51.994 --> 06:55.373
The trustees meeting isjust around the corner.

06:55.415 --> 06:56.833
Apparently the way the willis written,

06:56.874 --> 07:00.503
if I don't go soon the propertygoes into a receivership

07:00.545 --> 07:02.630
and becomes a biglegal mess.

07:02.630 --> 07:03.756
I understand.

07:03.798 --> 07:06.300
Do what you need to do,but please hurry back.

07:06.300 --> 07:08.636
I know I can get the trusteesto approve you.

07:08.678 --> 07:10.263
Thanks, Isabelle.

07:10.304 --> 07:12.557
I will be back beforeyou even know I'm gone.

07:12.598 --> 07:13.808
Oh, I hope so.

07:13.808 --> 07:15.643
Because if I don't geta successor soon

07:15.685 --> 07:18.479
they'll roast me like...

07:18.521 --> 07:19.856
Like...

07:19.897 --> 07:22.400
the great fire of Londonin 1666.

07:22.442 --> 07:24.026
Precisely.

07:24.068 --> 07:25.862
Oh, have a good flight.

07:25.903 --> 07:28.030
Thank you.

07:51.637 --> 07:53.681
Hello, I'm Lucy Windsor.

07:53.723 --> 07:56.559
As if I needed to be told that.

07:56.601 --> 07:58.436
I recognized youin an instant.

07:58.478 --> 07:59.937
Eleanor, of course.

07:59.979 --> 08:02.064
I'm so sorry.

08:02.106 --> 08:04.192
I didn't know you still workedat the estate.

08:04.233 --> 08:05.193
Oh, yes.

08:05.443 --> 08:07.028
How long has it been againsince you've been here?

08:07.069 --> 08:10.448
Ten years. I wanted to come backsooner to visit

08:10.490 --> 08:13.367
but work just kept me so busy.

08:13.409 --> 08:15.411
Your Aunt Grace understood.

08:15.453 --> 08:18.497
She was always so proud of you.

08:18.539 --> 08:24.837
She's sorely missed in town butshe lived a long and happy life.

08:24.879 --> 08:26.672
I just wish she werestill here.

08:26.714 --> 08:28.424
So do I, honey.

08:28.466 --> 08:29.717
Well, come along.

08:29.717 --> 08:32.553
You must be exhaustedafter your flight.

08:32.595 --> 08:34.722
Thank you.

08:35.264 --> 08:36.807
The back seat?

08:36.849 --> 08:39.769
Well, you are the mistressof the estate now, after all.

08:39.809 --> 08:42.647
But first an old friend.

09:08.714 --> 09:12.885
It is just as beautiful aroundhere as I remember.

09:12.927 --> 09:15.972
I had so many wonderfultimes here.

09:16.013 --> 09:17.723
And as I recall you and Duncan

09:17.765 --> 09:20.977
spent a great amount of timehere together, too.

09:21.018 --> 09:25.147
You were kind of sweet oneach other if memory serves.

09:25.189 --> 09:27.108
The follies of youth.

09:27.149 --> 09:29.944
Actually, Lucy, about Duncan-

09:29.986 --> 09:31.028
It's ok, Eleanor.

09:31.320 --> 09:37.159
He's one part of all of thisthat I am happy to forget.

09:49.714 --> 09:50.965
There she is.

09:51.007 --> 09:53.259
Right where you left her.

09:53.301 --> 09:55.886
Magical.

10:10.192 --> 10:12.194
[sheep baaing]

10:14.322 --> 10:16.032
What is all this?

10:16.073 --> 10:18.659
The welcoming committee?

10:18.701 --> 10:21.203
The fence in our pastureis falling down

10:21.245 --> 10:24.498
and your Aunt Grace could neversay no to visitors.

10:24.540 --> 10:26.208
You go on in and get settled,honey.

10:26.250 --> 10:27.168
Thank you.

10:27.209 --> 10:28.961
The door sticks a little.

10:29.003 --> 10:31.005
Got it.

10:45.311 --> 10:47.396
It's a little sticky, huh?

10:50.149 --> 10:51.317
Oh!

10:55.029 --> 10:56.197
Lucy?

10:56.197 --> 10:58.699
Duncan.

10:58.699 --> 11:01.202
What're you doingin my house?

11:01.202 --> 11:06.999
Uh... Lucy, what're you doingin my house?

11:07.041 --> 11:09.377
Your house? My house.

11:09.377 --> 11:10.878
What would give you that idea?

11:10.920 --> 11:12.338
It's not an idea it's a fact.

11:12.380 --> 11:13.714
That this is my house.

11:13.756 --> 11:15.257
No, mine.

11:16.842 --> 11:19.804
Ok, I think maybe there's beensome kind of a mistake.

11:19.845 --> 11:22.264
Why wouldn't Grace tell me  that she was leaving the house

11:22.306 --> 11:25.101
to both of us?

11:25.142 --> 11:26.894
Tell you? Why wouldn'tshe tell me?

11:26.894 --> 11:28.354
I don't know, maybe becauseI've been here

11:28.396 --> 11:30.314
and you've been in London?

11:33.067 --> 11:35.069
Regardless, it's perfectlyobvious

11:35.069 --> 11:38.322
there's been some sort ofa clerical error.

11:38.364 --> 11:40.116
You changed your hair.

11:43.744 --> 11:44.412
Yeah.

11:44.453 --> 11:46.455
[baaing]

11:46.497 --> 11:48.416
Shh.

11:51.168 --> 11:52.837
So how've you been, Lucy?

11:52.878 --> 11:53.754
Oh, I've been good.

11:54.004 --> 11:56.048
I've been- I've been really,really good.

11:56.090 --> 11:56.882
Good.

11:56.924 --> 11:58.884
Good.

11:58.926 --> 12:03.431
And you uh, you- you work insome museum in London I heard?

12:03.431 --> 12:04.390
Mmmhmm.

12:04.640 --> 12:06.058
Yeah, no, and I mighteven become its director.

12:06.100 --> 12:09.270
Knock... well, knock wood.

12:09.270 --> 12:11.272
And you, you're somefancy architect now?

12:11.272 --> 12:12.356
[laughs]

12:12.398 --> 12:13.566
Fancy? I don't know.

12:13.858 --> 12:16.193
I mean, I'm working for a bigcommercial firm up in Boston.

12:16.235 --> 12:17.445
I'm glad we'reall caught up.

12:17.486 --> 12:18.362
Excuse me.

12:18.612 --> 12:20.448
Eleanor, why didn't you tell meabout Duncan?

12:20.489 --> 12:21.740
I tried.

12:21.782 --> 12:22.867
You didn't wanna know.

12:22.908 --> 12:24.201
I'm gonna make some tea.

12:24.243 --> 12:28.122
Besides, it's high timeyou two buried the hatchet.

12:32.126 --> 12:33.210
Duncan.

12:33.252 --> 12:34.879
This has been lovely.

12:34.920 --> 12:38.716
I am going to go take a littlelook around.

12:38.758 --> 12:40.217
Be my guest.

12:40.259 --> 12:42.344
Or my guest.

12:52.813 --> 12:55.149
This place is still amazing.

12:55.191 --> 12:59.111
A window backto the 1890's.

12:59.153 --> 13:01.822
They don't build houseslike this anymore.

13:01.864 --> 13:02.948
And that's a good thing.

13:02.990 --> 13:05.826
Give me a modern condoany day.

13:05.868 --> 13:06.660
A place you can heat

13:06.911 --> 13:09.830
with up-to-date plumbingand electrical.

13:09.872 --> 13:11.874
It's still magical though.

13:11.916 --> 13:13.667
Yeah, it might look magical

13:13.709 --> 13:16.879
but this place is slowlyfalling apart.

13:16.921 --> 13:18.672
Note the buckets.

13:18.672 --> 13:20.841
It's seen some disrepair sincethe last time you visited,

13:20.883 --> 13:23.969
not to mention half of the roomsare already closed up.

13:27.264 --> 13:28.516
You see the problem?

13:28.557 --> 13:30.434
Yeah, I'm starting to.

13:35.981 --> 13:39.109
Grace used to hold herGilded Age Ball in here.

13:39.151 --> 13:42.988
Yep, this place has definitelyseen better days.

13:43.030 --> 13:44.240
The last two years I've beencoming down here

13:44.532 --> 13:47.076
on the weekends to help Graceout with the upkeep when I can.

13:47.117 --> 13:49.453
That's surprisingly charitableof you.

13:49.495 --> 13:53.040
A brief lapse in judgement,I assure you.

13:53.040 --> 13:55.960
But seriously, this placeis an absolute money pit

13:56.001 --> 13:59.171
and needs to be sold offat the earliest opportunity.

13:59.213 --> 14:01.215
Assuming you own it,which you don't.

14:01.257 --> 14:03.634
Which I do, and I'm wellon my way

14:03.676 --> 14:06.428
to coming up with a brilliantsales pitch for it.

14:06.470 --> 14:09.056
That is if the developer,Mr. Niven,

14:09.056 --> 14:11.016
is open to hearingmy presentation.

14:11.058 --> 14:12.476
Richard Niventhe billionaire?

14:12.518 --> 14:13.435
Ah, you've heard of him.

14:13.686 --> 14:16.397
Yeah, he specializesin building golf courses

14:16.397 --> 14:18.148
and I've heard he's interestedin opening

14:18.190 --> 14:19.400
a new one around here.

14:19.400 --> 14:22.945
Turn the estateinto a golf course? Seriously?

14:22.987 --> 14:23.863
Oh, I'm sorry.

14:24.113 --> 14:27.950
Did- did you have a better planfor this place?

14:27.992 --> 14:29.910
Not at this exact moment

14:29.952 --> 14:32.162
but surely there must bea better option

14:32.204 --> 14:36.083
than turning a magnificentestate into some putting green.

14:36.125 --> 14:38.419
This is 1890's at its finest.

14:38.419 --> 14:40.879
The stained glass,the marble floors-

14:40.921 --> 14:42.423
Out with the old,in with the new.

14:42.423 --> 14:45.426
Oooh! Duncan, how canyou be so blind

14:45.467 --> 14:47.761
to all the history around you?

14:47.761 --> 14:50.848
How can you be so blindto the bottom line?

14:50.889 --> 14:51.932
Listen, Frank Lloyd Wrong,

14:52.182 --> 14:55.769
you are not going to movea stone of this mansion.

14:55.811 --> 15:01.775
Ok. Well thenwhat do you suggest?

15:01.775 --> 15:03.319
This has got to besome big mistake.

15:03.360 --> 15:05.946
Aunt Grace would never put me insuch an impossible situation.

15:05.988 --> 15:08.240
I suggest that we geta little clarity

15:08.282 --> 15:10.284
from H .K. Rourke,Attorney at Law,

15:10.326 --> 15:12.536
and figure this outin the morning.

15:12.578 --> 15:13.287
Fine.

15:13.412 --> 15:14.496
Fine.

15:16.373 --> 15:18.042
Which hotel are you stayingat in town?

15:18.083 --> 15:18.667
Hmm?

15:18.709 --> 15:19.460
Hmm?

15:19.710 --> 15:21.545
Hotel? No, I'm not stayingat a hotel.

15:21.587 --> 15:24.173
I'm staying in the west wing.

15:24.214 --> 15:26.425
Of my mansion.

15:26.467 --> 15:27.927
Great.

15:27.968 --> 15:30.971
Then I'll be staying inthe east wing of my mansion.

15:31.013 --> 15:32.097
Great.

15:32.139 --> 15:33.432
Mmm.

15:34.933 --> 15:35.517
I'm gonna go that wayto the east wing.

15:35.684 --> 15:35.976
Yeah, that's fine.

15:36.226 --> 15:36.352
Thank you.

15:36.727 --> 15:37.311
After you.

15:37.311 --> 15:39.188
Mmmhmm.

15:39.480 --> 15:41.106
Stop watching me leave.

15:41.148 --> 15:43.108
You stop first.

15:47.529 --> 15:52.910
[phone ringing]

15:52.951 --> 15:55.955
Lucy, how's lifeon your estate?

15:55.996 --> 15:56.830
Where do I start?

15:57.081 --> 15:59.333
It turns outDuncan is staying here, too.

15:59.375 --> 16:00.334
Duncan?

16:00.376 --> 16:01.919
His father was the caretaker.

16:01.961 --> 16:03.337
He used to live here.

16:03.337 --> 16:06.173
But he's impossible,as always.

16:06.173 --> 16:09.093
Duncan thinks he inheritedhalf the estate.

16:09.134 --> 16:12.304
Co-owners of an estate,that sounds kind of romantic.

16:12.346 --> 16:16.517
Trust me, it is the oppositeof romantic.

16:16.517 --> 16:18.894
But I have to admit,he does look pretty good.

16:18.936 --> 16:20.396
Oh, details, please.

16:20.437 --> 16:22.981
What does he look like?

16:23.023 --> 16:25.859
A little bit like our statueof Marc Antony.

16:25.859 --> 16:27.319
But with the same flairfor betrayal.

16:27.361 --> 16:31.073
He's got some scheme to turnthe place into a golf course.

16:31.115 --> 16:32.533
A golf course?

16:32.533 --> 16:33.993
Well, that seems a bit daft.

16:34.034 --> 16:35.202
Exactly.

16:35.202 --> 16:37.204
But as soon as we figurethis whole thing out

16:37.204 --> 16:37.996
with the lawyers in the morning

16:38.205 --> 16:40.165
I am going to sendDuncan packing.

16:40.207 --> 16:41.917
Well, good luck, Lucy.

16:41.959 --> 16:44.253
Thanks, Jose.I'll need it.

16:54.513 --> 17:00.602
[loud grunts]

17:05.441 --> 17:08.277
What is happening out there?

17:17.243 --> 17:21.415
Hey. Hey, Duncan.

17:21.415 --> 17:23.125
Oh, a beautifulmorning to ya.

17:23.166 --> 17:25.919
I see you're still notan early riser.

17:25.919 --> 17:28.589
You ever hear of a little thingcalled jet lag?

17:28.630 --> 17:29.590
Vaguely.

17:29.923 --> 17:33.385
But I'm happy to help youget back on to local time.

17:35.429 --> 17:38.265
Ok, look.

17:38.265 --> 17:40.100
I'm a little tired.

17:40.142 --> 17:41.935
I could really use somemore sleep.

17:41.935 --> 17:43.604
Do you have to do thatright now?

17:43.604 --> 17:45.397
Well, if you want a hot shower

17:45.439 --> 17:47.608
before we go visitthe lawyers then yes,

17:47.649 --> 17:50.778
the water heater's down so Igotta fire up the old boiler.

17:50.819 --> 17:52.446
[loud grunt]

17:53.530 --> 17:57.284
Well, can you chop more quietly,please?

17:57.326 --> 17:59.119
Oh, you bet.

17:59.161 --> 18:01.246
[loud grunt]

18:03.499 --> 18:05.375
I give up.

18:09.546 --> 18:11.423
Good morning.

18:11.465 --> 18:12.633
Eleanor.

18:12.674 --> 18:14.676
You really didn't haveto do all this.

18:14.718 --> 18:16.553
Of course I did.

18:16.595 --> 18:17.930
Oh, it's such a delight

18:17.971 --> 18:21.225
to have you and Duncan togetherhere again.

18:21.266 --> 18:22.476
We're not together.

18:22.476 --> 18:24.478
Definitely not together!

18:24.520 --> 18:28.357
Uh, bad choice of words.

18:28.398 --> 18:30.609
One lump or two?

18:30.651 --> 18:32.152
Stevia?

18:35.280 --> 18:37.741
You are H .K. Rourke.

18:37.783 --> 18:41.578
Yes, but Hannah is fine.

18:41.620 --> 18:42.746
Hi, Duncan.

18:42.788 --> 18:45.165
Hello, Hannah.

18:45.207 --> 18:46.667
So you two know each other?

18:46.708 --> 18:49.670
Duncan took me tothe Newport Regatta.

18:49.670 --> 18:52.464
Oh.

18:52.506 --> 18:55.092
How lovely.

18:55.134 --> 18:57.803
Well, please. Sit down.

19:06.520 --> 19:08.772
First, let me extendmy sympathies.

19:08.814 --> 19:11.024
Grace was a big partof our community.

19:11.066 --> 19:13.527
Thank you. I really miss her.

19:13.569 --> 19:14.653
I do, too.

19:14.945 --> 19:17.281
That's why it's a little odd tobe talking business right now.

19:17.322 --> 19:21.702
And that brings us to thequestion of what happens next.

19:21.702 --> 19:22.661
Well, Duncan,

19:22.911 --> 19:26.164
regarding that mistakethat you called me about.

19:26.206 --> 19:28.208
It's actually not a mistake.

19:28.250 --> 19:29.293
Regarding Grace's will

19:29.334 --> 19:32.379
the situation is actuallyquite clear.

19:32.379 --> 19:36.550
Simply put, you bothown the estate.

19:36.550 --> 19:37.259
What?

19:37.301 --> 19:38.844
But how can that be?

19:38.886 --> 19:39.845
What she said.

19:39.887 --> 19:42.055
Grace was quite specificin her will.

19:42.097 --> 19:45.058
She arranged that you shouldboth own 50 percent.

19:45.058 --> 19:47.561
And I'm sorry that I couldn'texplain the full situation

19:47.603 --> 19:49.438
until you had both arrived,

19:49.479 --> 19:51.982
but Grace had sworn meto secrecy.

19:52.024 --> 19:53.233
Duncan,

19:53.233 --> 19:54.484
Grace mentionedin her will how much

19:54.526 --> 19:57.112
she appreciates everythingyou and your family did

19:57.154 --> 20:01.158
for her over the years and shewanted to extend her gratitude.

20:01.200 --> 20:04.286
And Lucy, Grace knewthat you loved that place

20:04.328 --> 20:06.496
as much as she didand you would always

20:06.538 --> 20:08.415
have its best interestsat heart.

20:08.415 --> 20:10.375
Which is why it makes absolutelyno sense

20:10.417 --> 20:11.710
that Grace would do this.

20:11.752 --> 20:13.378
Well, that much we agree on.

20:13.420 --> 20:15.964
Ok, so if I own half...

20:16.006 --> 20:18.425
And I own half.

20:18.425 --> 20:23.263
Then we have to cometo some sort of agreement.

20:23.263 --> 20:25.432
Look, the truth of the matter is

20:25.432 --> 20:30.103
the house is all that's left ofthe great Wycliff fortune.

20:30.103 --> 20:35.442
There's a small stipend to payfor Eleanor but that's it.

20:35.442 --> 20:38.779
And I'm here if you guyshave any more questions.

20:44.076 --> 20:46.662
Thank you very much for takingthe time, Hannah.

20:46.703 --> 20:48.830
We appreciate it.

20:49.831 --> 20:52.751
Oh hey, Duncan, um...really good news.

20:52.793 --> 20:54.544
My client, Mr. Niven,has agreed to hear

20:54.586 --> 20:57.297
your golf course presentation.

20:57.339 --> 20:58.715
I hope it helps.

20:58.757 --> 20:59.633
Thanks.

20:59.675 --> 21:00.759
Yeah.

21:05.430 --> 21:09.601
So Hannah is the one who foundyour potential buyer?

21:09.643 --> 21:12.646
Yeah, for a small 10 percentfinder's fee.

21:12.646 --> 21:14.231
She's just trying to help.

21:14.272 --> 21:16.400
In London we'd call that a weeconflict of interest.

21:16.441 --> 21:19.361
Ok. How about we finda civilized way

21:19.403 --> 21:21.822
of ironing this all out?

21:21.863 --> 21:23.782
Over breakfast maybe?

21:23.824 --> 21:26.910
Still got a weaknessfor waffles?

21:26.952 --> 21:28.328
I'm buying.

21:28.370 --> 21:30.414
You read my mind.

21:40.257 --> 21:41.883
Pancakes and waffles.

21:41.925 --> 21:42.676
Will do, Duncan.

21:42.718 --> 21:43.510
Thank you.

21:43.510 --> 21:44.886
And for you, miss?

21:46.638 --> 21:48.974
Wait, Lucy?

21:49.016 --> 21:50.767
Randall.

21:50.809 --> 21:52.686
It's so good to see you.

21:52.686 --> 21:56.732
Hi. Wow. Duncan and Lucy.

21:56.773 --> 21:58.567
Nice to see you twotogether again.

21:58.608 --> 22:00.444
(Both): We're not together.

22:00.485 --> 22:02.571
Duncan, you didn'ttell me Lucy's back in town.

22:02.612 --> 22:06.950
Well, that's because I'm assurprised as you are, my friend.

22:06.992 --> 22:09.244
Well, welcome home, Lucy.

22:09.286 --> 22:10.704
You still like your waffleswith strawberries

22:10.746 --> 22:12.539
and a pyramid of whipped cream?

22:12.539 --> 22:15.042
You have a fantastic memory.

22:15.042 --> 22:16.168
So what've you been up to?

22:16.460 --> 22:19.713
Just working here, helpingEleanor when she has errands,

22:19.755 --> 22:21.256
helping out with the festival.

22:21.298 --> 22:22.591
You should stop byif you have time.

22:22.632 --> 22:23.675
I'd love to.

22:23.717 --> 22:25.552
Ok. I'll put this in.

22:27.888 --> 22:30.807
Randall's still a hoot.

22:30.849 --> 22:32.434
At least he had the courtesyto send me

22:32.476 --> 22:34.603
a Christmas cardevery now and again.

22:34.644 --> 22:36.355
You left the country.

22:36.396 --> 22:39.441
You never repliedto any of my letters.

22:39.483 --> 22:41.443
You know what?

22:41.485 --> 22:43.362
Water under the bridge.

22:43.403 --> 22:45.822
So how is it thatyou're still so close

22:45.864 --> 22:47.324
with everyone herein Newton?

22:47.365 --> 22:48.617
I thought you were some

22:48.658 --> 22:51.411
high-flying architectin the big city.

22:51.411 --> 22:53.372
I have been coming downto Newton every weekend

22:53.413 --> 22:57.667
for one reason and one reasononly and that is the estate.

22:57.709 --> 22:59.336
It is a monster that needsconstant feeding

22:59.377 --> 23:01.380
and I am finished with it.

23:01.421 --> 23:03.757
But that house has been herefor over 100 years.

23:03.757 --> 23:05.425
How can you turn your backon it?

23:05.425 --> 23:10.597
Easy. Look, Lucy, if we couldjust sell this estate

23:10.639 --> 23:11.765
I would have the funds to start

23:12.015 --> 23:13.975
my own architecture firmand you could go back to London

23:14.017 --> 23:16.144
with a tidy little nest egg.

23:16.186 --> 23:17.562
What do you say?

23:17.604 --> 23:19.439
But if Niven goes for it,

23:19.439 --> 23:20.941
what happens to the estate?

23:20.982 --> 23:23.443
Well, the plans that I suggestedwould see the grounds

23:23.485 --> 23:26.446
opened up for the fairwaysand we would probably have

23:26.488 --> 23:28.824
to lose the coach house,the gardens-

23:28.865 --> 23:30.617
Bulldoze the gardens?

23:30.659 --> 23:33.286
Duncan, over my dead body.

23:33.328 --> 23:35.705
Do you have any ideawhat it takes to maintain

23:35.747 --> 23:37.874
an estate like this?

23:37.916 --> 23:42.712
No, but I wanna leave itin good hands.

23:42.754 --> 23:43.797
I don't know, maybe I couldget it designated

23:44.047 --> 23:46.633
as a historical landmarkand then I could start

23:46.633 --> 23:48.593
applying for grantsto protect it.

23:48.635 --> 23:51.304
We would be lucky if Nivenpicked it up.

23:51.346 --> 23:52.639
Our other option is putting iton the market

23:52.931 --> 23:57.644
and honestly, at this rate, itwouldn't even pass inspection.

23:57.686 --> 23:59.396
Ok, so whatdo you propose?

23:59.438 --> 24:01.898
I suggest that we sell offa few odds and ends

24:01.940 --> 24:04.067
so we have the fundsto patch up the roof

24:04.109 --> 24:05.485
while we try to figure out

24:05.485 --> 24:07.612
what to do withthe rest of the place.

24:07.654 --> 24:09.865
Fine.

24:09.906 --> 24:11.116
Ooh.

24:16.621 --> 24:19.458
Did you know that Belgianwaffles were invented

24:19.499 --> 24:22.669
in the 1800's by the PrinceBishop of Liege?

24:22.711 --> 24:24.629
Nobody knows that, Lucy.

24:24.671 --> 24:26.673
[laughs]

24:26.715 --> 24:28.717
Well, what do you think,dad?

24:28.758 --> 24:30.594
My money's on Lucy.

24:30.635 --> 24:32.637
She always was headstrongas a kid.

24:32.679 --> 24:35.015
True, but Duncan'salways got a trick or two

24:35.015 --> 24:36.099
up his sleeve.

24:36.141 --> 24:37.517
It's a shame they can't just-

24:37.559 --> 24:40.729
Work together. I know.

24:40.770 --> 24:45.567
Of course, maybe theyjust need a nudge.

24:55.952 --> 25:00.123
Coffee. Coffee. Coffee.

25:00.165 --> 25:01.500
Coff-

25:01.541 --> 25:02.292
What? No, out.

25:02.334 --> 25:03.001
Out.

25:03.043 --> 25:03.960
Shoo. Shoo. Shoo.

25:04.002 --> 25:04.836
Shoo. Shoo.

25:04.878 --> 25:05.712
Go on.

25:05.712 --> 25:06.838
Out. Out. Out. Out.

25:06.880 --> 25:07.923
Go!

25:09.883 --> 25:11.092
Morning.

25:11.134 --> 25:12.719
Where's Eleanor?

25:12.719 --> 25:13.678
Uh, she left a note.

25:13.929 --> 25:17.432
She went to town to help outwith the festival

25:17.474 --> 25:19.559
and left breakfast on the stove.

25:19.559 --> 25:22.395
Meanwhile, why don'tyou put your world class

25:22.395 --> 25:25.899
architectural skills to use andfix the lock on the kitchen door

25:25.899 --> 25:28.151
so Percy will staywhere he belongs?

25:28.193 --> 25:29.945
Percy?

25:29.986 --> 25:33.240
I mean the sheep that justpushed his way into the kitchen.

25:33.240 --> 25:34.074
Why Percy?

25:34.115 --> 25:35.492
Because he's so persistent.

25:35.534 --> 25:37.953
Huh. Sounds like somebodyelse I know.

25:37.994 --> 25:39.746
I'll add it to the list.

25:39.788 --> 25:41.456
So I've totaled the amountof money we'll need

25:41.498 --> 25:44.668
for the essential fixes beforewe can even show this place.

25:44.709 --> 25:46.461
We'll need to touch upthe paint,

25:46.503 --> 25:50.632
fix some of these windows,and, of course, pay the roofers.

25:50.674 --> 25:52.717
Better get started.

25:52.759 --> 25:54.553
This house has lastedfor 100 years.

25:54.594 --> 25:56.596
I think it can make itthrough breakfast.

25:56.638 --> 25:58.974
No time like the present.

26:04.980 --> 26:07.899
Duncan. Duncan, what're youdoing with those?

26:07.941 --> 26:10.443
We need money to fixthe roof, remember?

26:10.443 --> 26:12.570
So I thought we could sell offa few of these things

26:12.612 --> 26:14.531
at the antique auctionin Newton.

26:14.573 --> 26:15.782
It's just collecting dust.

26:15.824 --> 26:17.951
But these areAunt Grace's things

26:17.993 --> 26:20.078
and Wycliffe family heirlooms.

26:20.120 --> 26:21.288
Sacrificing themselvesto keep this house

26:21.621 --> 26:24.833
from falling apart seems likethe most noble duty of all.

26:24.874 --> 26:25.792
It's just random stuff.

26:25.792 --> 26:26.626
Random stuff?

26:26.835 --> 26:28.920
That is a 19th centuryoil painting.

26:28.962 --> 26:29.963
Yeah.

26:29.963 --> 26:32.716
Of, like, trees.

26:32.757 --> 26:35.635
And that antique Venetian vaseis in perfect condition.

26:35.677 --> 26:36.845
What, this old thing?

26:36.886 --> 26:38.930
Oh!

26:38.972 --> 26:41.141
Oh, those chandeliersin the Great Hall

26:41.182 --> 26:42.642
are probably worth something.

26:42.642 --> 26:47.731
No. Duncan, I love those.

26:47.772 --> 26:49.065
Ok.

26:49.107 --> 26:50.150
How about this?

26:50.150 --> 26:50.984
We've got dozens of these.

26:51.234 --> 26:51.985
Those are emblematic ofthe fascination

26:52.444 --> 26:55.739
in the 1890's of botanyand floral history.

26:55.780 --> 26:57.991
We have to keep at least one.

26:57.991 --> 27:02.245
Ok. What is your obsessionwith history?

27:03.997 --> 27:08.001
No, those are treasures and...

27:08.043 --> 27:11.046
this is Aunt Grace's diary.

27:11.087 --> 27:12.672
We certainly can't sell that.

27:12.672 --> 27:15.675
Ok, granted, that was a mistake.

27:15.717 --> 27:18.803
What about this paintingwith the pretty girl in it?

27:23.808 --> 27:25.769
Haha, very funny.

27:25.810 --> 27:28.355
This Victorian hall standis an antique.

27:28.355 --> 27:30.690
Lucy, be practical for once.

27:30.732 --> 27:33.360
We need to fix this roof.

27:33.401 --> 27:34.903
[sighs]

27:34.944 --> 27:39.324
Ok. Fine. But make it quick.

27:41.284 --> 27:43.078
Ready?

27:46.873 --> 27:48.166
Ok.

27:50.168 --> 27:52.295
And this one?

27:55.173 --> 27:56.966
I'm proud of you.

27:57.008 --> 27:58.218
I'm going to give Randall a call

27:58.510 --> 27:59.969
and see if he can give us a handto bring this down to auction.

28:00.011 --> 28:03.056
I'm going with you to makesure you get a fair price.

28:03.098 --> 28:04.933
Deal.

28:16.820 --> 28:20.615
The 1890's were a uniquemoment in our town's history

28:20.657 --> 28:23.076
when Henry Wycliff decidedto build his estate here

28:23.118 --> 28:25.745
and ended up helping buildmuch of the town.

28:25.745 --> 28:27.914
And the Wycliff's continuedthat tradition.

28:27.956 --> 28:30.667
Henry's grandson, Arthur,and his wife, Grace,

28:30.709 --> 28:34.003
built our city park there.

28:34.045 --> 28:36.297
I have nothing but happymemories here.

28:36.339 --> 28:40.468
Finally somethingwe can agree on.

28:43.012 --> 28:49.477
[piano playing]

28:49.519 --> 28:59.529
♪

28:59.946 --> 29:00.697
Sold.

29:00.947 --> 29:03.950
One antique oil paintingfor $1,200.

29:03.992 --> 29:07.871
Not bad. That's $3,000 in total.

29:07.912 --> 29:09.706
Alright, I'll admit it.

29:09.748 --> 29:12.333
You have an eye for this stuff.

29:12.375 --> 29:15.295
Oh my, a compliment.

29:15.295 --> 29:16.421
Will the wonders ever cease?

29:16.463 --> 29:17.964
Alright.

29:18.006 --> 29:19.841
[laughs]

29:23.303 --> 29:26.264
It's like travelingback in time.

29:26.306 --> 29:28.266
It's fascinating, isn't it?

29:28.308 --> 29:29.100
Mmmhmm.

29:29.142 --> 29:30.143
Yeah, fascinating.

29:30.185 --> 29:31.895
You know, that beer gardenback there

29:31.936 --> 29:33.354
sounds pretty fascinating, too.

29:33.396 --> 29:34.731
You want to join me?

29:34.772 --> 29:36.191
You go ahead.

29:36.232 --> 29:38.151
I'm going to browse.

29:41.112 --> 29:43.490
Lucy Windsor?

29:43.531 --> 29:45.450
Is that you?

29:45.492 --> 29:48.828
Mr. and Mrs. Jorgensen.

29:48.870 --> 29:50.747
You remember my husband Marcus?

29:50.788 --> 29:52.040
Of course.

29:52.081 --> 29:53.750
Lucy, it's been ages.

29:53.791 --> 29:56.169
Randall told us you werein town.

29:56.169 --> 29:59.297
Grace would be so happyto have you back home.

29:59.339 --> 30:01.216
You're here to handlethe estate, no doubt?

30:01.257 --> 30:02.300
Yes.

30:02.342 --> 30:06.221
And give Hannah Rourkea little competition?

30:09.307 --> 30:14.229
You and Duncan were prettyserious back in the day.

30:14.270 --> 30:16.022
Are they, uh, dating?

30:16.022 --> 30:19.984
No, but Hannah's the top shotin the darts contest every year

30:20.026 --> 30:22.695
and Duncan's got a bullseyeon his back

30:22.737 --> 30:24.030
whether he knows it or not.

30:24.072 --> 30:25.740
[laughs]

30:25.782 --> 30:30.245
Well, she can tag and releasehim for all I'm concerned.

30:30.286 --> 30:32.372
Well, Eleanor saysthat you're undecided

30:32.372 --> 30:34.374
about what's to comeof the estate.

30:34.374 --> 30:37.836
Yes, things are up in the airbut we'll figure it out.

30:37.877 --> 30:41.172
Lucy, you must come bythe cafe for dinner

30:41.214 --> 30:43.967
to welcome you back to town.

30:44.008 --> 30:48.054
I would love to but I'm a littleconcerned about leaving Duncan

30:48.096 --> 30:49.305
and the estate alone,

30:49.347 --> 30:53.393
goodness knows what he'll tryto sell off next.

30:53.393 --> 30:55.395
Well, bring him along, then.

30:55.436 --> 30:56.563
The more the merrier.

30:56.604 --> 30:58.481
Yeah.

30:58.523 --> 31:00.024
Ok. Sure.

31:00.066 --> 31:01.025
See you then.

31:01.067 --> 31:02.527
Ok.

31:16.541 --> 31:18.418
We'll take it.

31:20.295 --> 31:21.504
Well, that's very galant of you.

31:21.546 --> 31:23.840
Are you buying me a giftwith our money?

31:23.882 --> 31:25.341
No, I got this.

31:25.383 --> 31:28.553
We need every cent of ourantique money for the repairs.

31:28.595 --> 31:29.429
Ok, I take back what I said.

31:29.679 --> 31:33.224
You always did havea tiny sweet spot.

31:33.266 --> 31:34.142
Mmm.

31:34.183 --> 31:35.727
So now you remember.

31:35.768 --> 31:37.770
Too bad posterity will rememberyou as the guy

31:37.770 --> 31:40.898
who tried to turn a landmarkinto a sand trap.

31:40.940 --> 31:45.445
Right. And uh, remind me,what was your idea again?

31:45.445 --> 31:47.989
I told you, I'm thinking on it.

31:48.031 --> 31:50.033
Oh, can I grab one of these?

31:50.074 --> 31:51.492
Egg cream?

31:53.244 --> 31:56.122
You know the wayto a girl's heart.

31:56.164 --> 31:58.291
Just like old times.

32:01.502 --> 32:04.088
Ooh, those look pretty yummy.

32:04.130 --> 32:04.714
Yeah, it smells good.

32:04.756 --> 32:06.341
Yeah.

32:06.382 --> 32:09.510
Oh, look at these.

32:16.476 --> 32:17.935
Wow.

32:17.977 --> 32:20.355
Can you believe we oncedressed like this?

32:20.396 --> 32:22.482
Decades from now some modernarchitect will be saying

32:22.523 --> 32:26.819
the same thingabout photographs of us.

32:26.861 --> 32:30.865
Oh, I love imaginingwho these people were.

32:30.907 --> 32:36.579
Where they worked, where theylived, who they loved.

32:36.621 --> 32:39.999
I forgot how much I lovedthis festival.

32:39.999 --> 32:42.043
The antiques and the costumes.

32:42.085 --> 32:43.878
It's all so unique.

32:43.920 --> 32:46.089
Shame it's only once a year.

32:46.130 --> 32:49.050
It's too bad it can't lastall ye-

32:50.510 --> 32:52.971
What?

32:53.012 --> 32:54.514
Nothing.

32:54.555 --> 32:57.016
Can we go backto the estate now?

32:57.016 --> 32:58.601
Yeah.

33:00.353 --> 33:02.939
(Josephine): So how's the life of leisure?

33:02.980 --> 33:05.358
A lot more work than I expected.

33:05.358 --> 33:07.068
And Duncan?

33:07.110 --> 33:09.529
He's still got aNapoleon complex

33:09.529 --> 33:12.907
mixed with a dashof Genghis Khan.

33:12.949 --> 33:15.159
But in spite of Duncan's plans

33:15.201 --> 33:17.120
I have an idea to savethis place.

33:17.161 --> 33:20.164
Uh-oh, I can hear the wheels turning from here.

33:20.206 --> 33:21.249
What's your plan?

33:21.541 --> 33:24.836
Well, it's just that there'sso much history in this town

33:24.877 --> 33:27.672
and I realized the estatedoesn't have to be

33:27.714 --> 33:30.383
just a historical landmark.

33:30.425 --> 33:32.552
Visitors can step back in time.

33:32.593 --> 33:35.555
Like that colonial Williamsburgmy nephew visited.

33:35.555 --> 33:36.639
Exactly.

33:36.931 --> 33:40.810
The town is the perfect stopon the mansion tourist circuit

33:40.852 --> 33:44.605
and our little Newton doesn'teven have one museum.

33:44.647 --> 33:47.859
The challenge is going to behow to make it happen.

33:47.900 --> 33:49.527
Well, if anyone can makeit happen it's you.

33:49.569 --> 33:51.362
Oh, and Lucy, don't forget your conference call

33:51.404 --> 33:53.656
with the trustees isin four days.

33:53.698 --> 33:55.199
I'll be ready.

33:55.241 --> 33:56.534
Thank you, Josephine.

33:56.576 --> 33:57.410
Bye.

33:57.410 --> 33:59.495
Bye.

34:06.252 --> 34:09.422
You seriously thinkthat plan's gonna work?

34:09.464 --> 34:11.174
Were you eavesdropping?

34:11.215 --> 34:12.216
I can't help it.

34:12.257 --> 34:13.426
Echo-y halls.

34:13.426 --> 34:15.261
Oh.

34:15.303 --> 34:17.304
You're not afraid of a littlecompetition, are you?

34:17.346 --> 34:19.806
Afraid? Not a chance.

34:19.849 --> 34:23.603
So as co-owners of the estateyou don't mind if I present

34:23.643 --> 34:26.522
an alternative proposalto your potential buyer?

34:26.563 --> 34:27.398
Mr. Niven?

34:27.440 --> 34:28.190
Mmmhmm.

34:28.232 --> 34:29.275
Of course not.

34:29.609 --> 34:32.027
It'll keep you out of my hairwhile I work on my proposal.

34:32.070 --> 34:33.362
Please, have at it.

34:33.404 --> 34:35.031
Ok.

34:35.072 --> 34:37.116
And whichever ideaNiven supports

34:37.116 --> 34:38.826
we both agree to approve.

34:38.868 --> 34:41.829
Sure. I'm game.

34:41.871 --> 34:44.165
Have fun.

34:48.585 --> 34:51.297
I'm gonna save your house,Aunt Grace.

34:52.632 --> 35:02.642
[classical music plays]♪

35:04.143 --> 35:07.105
You mind turning downyour music?

35:07.146 --> 35:08.272
Really?

35:08.314 --> 35:10.525
Come on, Duncan.It helps me think.

35:10.566 --> 35:14.654
It literally prevents mefrom thinking.

35:14.695 --> 35:16.572
Fine.

35:17.782 --> 35:23.496
[starts humming]

35:23.538 --> 35:25.373
Ok, now you're humming.

35:25.414 --> 35:27.708
Lucy, there are literally 39other rooms in this place.

35:27.750 --> 35:29.377
You sure you don't wanna workin one of them?

35:29.418 --> 35:34.340
Since the estate's half mine Ibelieve this table is half mine

35:34.382 --> 35:36.509
and this room inspires me.

35:36.551 --> 35:39.428
How's that presentationcoming along?

35:39.470 --> 35:40.346
Great.

35:40.638 --> 35:42.431
Did I tell you aboutmy idea to turn the solarium

35:42.473 --> 35:44.475
into a botanical exhibit?

35:44.517 --> 35:45.685
Did I tell you about my plan

35:45.726 --> 35:48.688
to turn the solariuminto a pro shop?

35:48.688 --> 35:51.649
Huh. According to my web search

35:51.691 --> 35:56.529
there are already four othergolf courses within 30 miles.

35:56.571 --> 35:58.698
Does this areareally need another?

35:58.698 --> 36:02.368
According to my researchit could take years

36:02.410 --> 36:05.621
to get a site declareda historical landmark.

36:05.663 --> 36:06.706
Tsk tsk.

36:06.706 --> 36:08.291
Ah.

36:08.332 --> 36:10.626
So you've been researchingmy idea.

36:10.668 --> 36:13.087
Guess my plan's got youa little intrigued.

36:13.129 --> 36:15.381
Yeah, guilty. Intrigued.

36:15.423 --> 36:18.801
At how completely impracticalyou still are.

36:20.469 --> 36:21.554
But just for argument's sake,

36:21.596 --> 36:23.181
how would you possiblyfund this?

36:23.222 --> 36:24.599
I'm going to devote partof the house

36:24.640 --> 36:27.518
to showcase antique vendorsand local craftspeople

36:27.560 --> 36:30.271
from town and we couldsell their goods here.

36:30.313 --> 36:31.689
It's called revenue.

36:31.731 --> 36:32.565
Revenue.

36:32.565 --> 36:33.399
Mmmhmm.

36:33.608 --> 36:34.734
And that revenue would beenough to keep

36:34.775 --> 36:37.570
this entire place running?

36:37.612 --> 36:39.322
I think it's worth a try.

36:39.363 --> 36:43.284
I think you still gotyour head up in the clouds.

36:43.326 --> 36:45.745
[turns music back on]

36:45.786 --> 36:49.248
♪

36:49.290 --> 36:50.249
Alright, you know what?

36:50.249 --> 36:51.500
If we're going to sharethis estate

36:51.542 --> 36:53.628
then maybe we should setsome house rules.

36:53.669 --> 36:54.545
Great idea.

36:54.795 --> 36:56.589
For starters how aboutno drying your laundry

36:56.589 --> 36:58.841
on the priceless antiques?

36:58.883 --> 36:59.926
Fine.

37:00.217 --> 37:04.597
If you agree to no more thanone hour of your music a day.

37:04.639 --> 37:05.848
Fine.

37:05.890 --> 37:07.224
Now, if that's all,

37:07.266 --> 37:09.727
we are due at the pubfor dinner tonight.

37:09.769 --> 37:11.479
We?

37:11.520 --> 37:13.189
Look, I said yesfor both of us.

37:13.231 --> 37:14.273
I couldn't help it.

37:14.315 --> 37:15.399
Yeah, that's great.I'm starving.

37:15.441 --> 37:17.443
I'll see you downstairsin five minutes.

37:28.871 --> 37:30.623
Well, look who's here.

37:30.623 --> 37:32.792
Our guests of honor.

37:32.792 --> 37:34.001
What's all this?

37:34.043 --> 37:35.044
It's nothing.

37:35.336 --> 37:39.298
Just a little dinner to welcomeyou back home to Newton.

37:39.340 --> 37:41.467
You didn't have to do this.

37:41.467 --> 37:42.593
Nonsense.

37:42.635 --> 37:46.389
You two are officiallyour guests of honor.

37:48.307 --> 37:49.392
Thank you.

37:50.768 --> 37:51.811
I sense a trap.

37:52.103 --> 37:58.359
So I hope these rumors aren'ttrue of selling the estate

37:58.401 --> 38:00.861
and high-tailing it out of town.

38:00.903 --> 38:03.739
You wanna take this one?

38:06.492 --> 38:08.202
We're still trying to figurethings out,

38:08.244 --> 38:15.126
but I am working on a planto save the old place.

38:15.167 --> 38:17.712
Well, Wycliff Houseis this town's heritage

38:17.753 --> 38:20.214
and I can't think of anyonebetter than you two

38:20.256 --> 38:22.383
to watch over it.

38:22.425 --> 38:24.552
To Wycliff House.

38:24.593 --> 38:26.971
[together] To Wycliff House.

38:28.764 --> 38:29.640
You know, Lucy,

38:29.890 --> 38:32.852
I remember allthose summers you visited Grace.

38:32.852 --> 38:35.229
You always seemedso at home here.

38:35.271 --> 38:39.025
Name one thing that Londonhas that we don't have here.

38:39.025 --> 38:41.777
Ok, uh...

38:41.819 --> 38:42.987
the museums.

38:43.029 --> 38:43.738
[laughs]

38:43.946 --> 38:45.865
I'd say this whole townis a museum.

38:45.906 --> 38:47.324
[laughter]

38:47.366 --> 38:48.826
Can't argue that.

38:51.370 --> 38:56.625
Look, all joking aside,I love it here.

38:56.667 --> 39:00.046
But my dream job iswaiting for me back in England.

39:00.046 --> 39:01.505
Dream job, huh?

39:01.547 --> 39:05.301
Well, I'll admit a dream job'spretty serious.

39:05.342 --> 39:10.389
But desserts like thisonly come once in a lifetime.

39:10.389 --> 39:11.474
Desserts?

39:12.641 --> 39:15.394
(Group): Oooh.

39:15.394 --> 39:18.022
Truly, you didn't haveto do all this.

39:18.064 --> 39:20.441
Oh, but we did.

39:20.483 --> 39:24.153
See, your Aunt Grace has helpedevery single person in this town

39:24.195 --> 39:27.948
in one way or another and Marcusand I got engaged at the ball

39:27.990 --> 39:30.409
that your aunt used to throwevery year

39:30.409 --> 39:32.912
and Randall learned to rideat your stables

39:32.953 --> 39:35.831
and it's high timethat we repaid the favor.

39:35.873 --> 39:36.999
Welcome back.

39:37.041 --> 39:37.917
Welcome back.

39:37.958 --> 39:39.668
Welcome back, Lucy.

39:45.966 --> 39:49.428
I love this part of the estate.

39:49.428 --> 39:52.723
I had forgotten how hospitableeveryone is in this town.

39:52.765 --> 39:55.976
Yeah, some thingsnever change.

39:56.018 --> 39:56.977
I'm starting to get the feeling

39:57.228 --> 40:01.690
that they're trying to convinceus to stay.

40:01.732 --> 40:04.944
Well, I could think of worsethings than staying.

40:11.826 --> 40:14.120
You hear that?

40:15.121 --> 40:16.956
What?

40:16.956 --> 40:23.587
The sound of the cricketsinstead of us squabbling.

40:23.629 --> 40:25.756
It's pretty nice.

40:29.385 --> 40:32.304
Hey, tell me something.

40:32.304 --> 40:37.977
What happened that last summerwe were here together?

40:38.018 --> 40:40.312
You were headed offto grad school.

40:40.312 --> 40:45.651
You were gonna be thousandsof miles away.

40:45.651 --> 40:47.778
How could it have worked?

40:47.820 --> 40:50.990
So you just cut and ran?

40:50.990 --> 40:52.867
It was the practicalthing to do.

40:52.908 --> 40:53.826
Mmm.

40:53.868 --> 40:56.036
Practical. Again.

40:56.078 --> 40:58.456
Someone had to be.

40:58.497 --> 41:02.334
You were always the dreamer.

41:02.334 --> 41:07.465
Ok, look. I... I know my ideais just a pipe dream

41:07.506 --> 41:08.507
and you're right.

41:08.799 --> 41:11.510
It does take forever to geta historical designation

41:11.510 --> 41:15.723
but I can't just sit byand watch all of this go away.

41:15.764 --> 41:21.020
This estate is home to way toomany happy memories for me and-

41:21.020 --> 41:21.896
and Aunt Grace-

41:21.937 --> 41:24.064
I miss Grace, too.

41:24.106 --> 41:26.901
You forget, I lived hereyear round.

41:26.942 --> 41:30.029
I know every inchof this place.

41:30.029 --> 41:31.822
I grew up here.

41:31.864 --> 41:34.366
I went to Bostonto start over

41:34.408 --> 41:36.869
but Grace needed my helpand this estate

41:36.869 --> 41:38.787
and all of its needs keptcalling me back

41:38.829 --> 41:40.498
over and over and over.

41:40.539 --> 41:42.958
I need to be done with it.

41:43.000 --> 41:46.045
This firm is the most importantthing to me.

41:46.045 --> 41:49.048
I've always been focusedon the past

41:49.048 --> 41:52.092
and you've always been focusedon the future.

41:56.055 --> 41:58.933
Who says historyhas to repeat itself?

41:58.974 --> 41:59.934
What do you mean?

41:59.975 --> 42:01.060
Ok, well let's face it.

42:01.101 --> 42:03.854
A house dividedcannot stand.

42:03.896 --> 42:04.772
Go on.

42:05.064 --> 42:09.944
I want a historical site,you want a golf course.

42:09.985 --> 42:12.238
Why can't we have both?

42:12.279 --> 42:15.491
I am not following you.

42:15.532 --> 42:18.577
How about a resortthat showcases history?

42:18.619 --> 42:22.498
It's the best of both worlds.

42:22.539 --> 42:23.916
Interesting.

42:23.958 --> 42:26.961
But Niven is expecting a golfcourse, plain and simple.

42:27.002 --> 42:28.545
But he's a business man,

42:28.587 --> 42:30.798
and we'd be doubling thepotential revenue stream

42:30.839 --> 42:33.092
and preserving history.

42:33.092 --> 42:36.720
More tourists flockto this town every year.

42:36.762 --> 42:38.097
That's an opportunity.

42:38.097 --> 42:39.098
True.

42:39.098 --> 42:42.184
And we could hold Grace'sGilded Age Ball

42:42.226 --> 42:43.477
just like she used to do

42:43.519 --> 42:45.479
and really show offthe estate to Niven

42:45.521 --> 42:47.189
the way it's meant to be seen.

42:47.231 --> 42:48.899
That seems very ambitious.

42:48.941 --> 42:53.988
We have two daysto come up with a sales pitch.

42:54.029 --> 42:56.031
What do you think?

42:59.451 --> 43:03.247
A golf course that doublesas a history park.

43:03.289 --> 43:05.499
Yeah, why not?

43:05.541 --> 43:06.625
Maybe it's the moonlight

43:06.625 --> 43:11.588
but I think you might beon to something.

43:11.630 --> 43:14.049
Deal?

43:14.091 --> 43:16.802
Deal.

43:16.844 --> 43:19.847
[laughs]

43:26.812 --> 43:28.606
So the fountain stays put.

43:28.647 --> 43:29.398
That's right.

43:29.648 --> 43:30.399
And we won't haveto move a stone.

43:30.858 --> 43:35.154
And then the Great Hallbecomes our grand lobby.

43:35.195 --> 43:37.781
We make a pretty good team.

43:37.823 --> 43:39.825
Like Hamilton and Burr.

43:39.867 --> 43:42.619
Before all that unpleasantness.

43:42.661 --> 43:45.122
Sure. What's next?

44:28.999 --> 44:29.917
You know, for an architect

44:30.167 --> 44:31.794
you have some prettygood hands-on skills.

44:31.835 --> 44:34.922
Thanks. My dad used to let mehelp him fix things

44:34.963 --> 44:36.256
around the house.

44:36.298 --> 44:38.217
Do you know that Aunt Graceand Arthur

44:38.217 --> 44:42.137
were married hereon the estate?

44:42.179 --> 44:45.307
I wonder how many other weddingsthis property has seen.

44:45.349 --> 44:47.017
Weddings.

44:47.059 --> 44:49.895
That's not a bad ideato add to the proposal.

44:49.937 --> 44:51.855
Yeah.

44:51.897 --> 44:57.903
You know, courtship in the late1800's was truly fascinating.

44:57.945 --> 45:00.656
A gentleman's invitation toa dance was often delivered

45:00.697 --> 45:04.952
to a lady in a letter to avoidany misunderstanding,

45:04.993 --> 45:09.665
and suitors would woo theirbeloved with moonlit serenades

45:09.706 --> 45:13.127
and poetry and acts of chivalry,of course.

45:13.168 --> 45:14.378
Sounds exhausting.

45:14.420 --> 45:16.088
[laughs]

45:16.088 --> 45:17.923
Will you help me move this,please?

45:17.965 --> 45:20.300
Sure.

45:20.342 --> 45:21.802
Oh, watch out!

45:32.229 --> 45:34.148
Chivalrous.

45:35.607 --> 45:38.235
Well, I think I'm gonna gowash up

45:38.277 --> 45:43.782
and then what do you say we headto the festival?

45:43.824 --> 45:46.160
Perfect. We can spread the wordabout the ball.

45:49.413 --> 45:51.665
Oh, it is so greatthat you're bringing back

45:51.707 --> 45:53.250
Grace's Gilded Age Ball.

45:53.292 --> 45:55.377
Well, it is the finaleof our pitch to Niven

45:55.419 --> 45:57.045
to preserve Wycliff House.

45:57.087 --> 45:58.297
Give me those.

45:58.338 --> 46:00.215
I'll put these up around town.

46:00.257 --> 46:03.469
That'll show Niven whatWycliff means to this town.

46:03.469 --> 46:04.470
Take a shot, folks.

46:04.470 --> 46:05.971
Take a shot,and win a prize.

46:05.971 --> 46:08.307
Come on. Take a shotand win a prize.

46:08.348 --> 46:11.852
Take home a beautiful antiquevase from the Gilded Age.

46:11.894 --> 46:14.897
Miss, what about you?

46:14.938 --> 46:15.856
Oh, no, no, no.

46:15.898 --> 46:16.940
Thank you very much.

46:16.982 --> 46:18.358
Come on, Lucy. It looks fun.

46:18.400 --> 46:21.195
I bet you picked up some skillsback in England.

46:21.236 --> 46:23.489
The only targets I'mused to hitting these days

46:23.489 --> 46:26.074
are third quarter donations. No.

46:26.116 --> 46:27.367
Thank you. No thank you.

46:27.409 --> 46:28.327
I get it.

46:28.368 --> 46:30.996
You're scared.That's cool.

46:30.996 --> 46:33.332
Scared?

46:33.332 --> 46:38.378
Ok. Since you put itthat way,

46:38.420 --> 46:40.339
I'll take two turns.

46:40.380 --> 46:43.175
I'll show you who is scared.

46:51.517 --> 46:51.850
Blech!

46:52.017 --> 46:52.726
What was that?

46:53.101 --> 46:54.269
Your technique isall over the place.

46:54.311 --> 46:56.313
Look, may I?

46:57.523 --> 47:00.150
So, the thing with darts is

47:00.192 --> 47:05.405
you gotta line it upfrom your shoulders.

47:05.447 --> 47:08.450
Raise your elbow.

47:08.492 --> 47:09.785
Good to go.

47:09.827 --> 47:14.248
Alright. Here goes.

47:14.289 --> 47:15.916
Hey, look who's here.

47:15.958 --> 47:18.210
Looks like you're getting intothe spirit of things, Lucy.

47:18.252 --> 47:19.461
We're just taking a break

47:19.503 --> 47:21.213
from the estate to enjoythe festival.

47:21.213 --> 47:22.923
You know what?This does look like fun.

47:22.965 --> 47:23.882
I'm gonna play, too.

47:24.216 --> 47:27.219
Hannah, you clear outall my prizes every year.

47:27.261 --> 47:29.054
Thank you.

47:36.144 --> 47:38.313
Duncan's been reallymysterious lately,

47:38.355 --> 47:40.190
what have you two been up to?

47:40.232 --> 47:43.235
Just trying to do what's bestfor our place.

47:43.235 --> 47:45.904
Well, I've set up the perfectopportunity for you.

47:45.946 --> 47:48.198
I hope you're ready for Niven.

47:48.240 --> 47:51.618
Maybe your sales pitch is moreon target than your dart game.

47:57.082 --> 48:01.920
And then you can be done withthe estate and head back home.

48:01.920 --> 48:04.339
That is still the plan,isn't it?

48:04.381 --> 48:06.925
Yes.

48:06.967 --> 48:09.136
Yes, it is.

48:09.177 --> 48:12.472
Don't feel bad, Lucy.It's an acquired skill.

48:16.435 --> 48:20.230
You know, at Oxford we startwith our weaker hand

48:20.272 --> 48:22.608
when we play freshmen.

48:25.444 --> 48:28.947
[applause]

48:28.989 --> 48:31.909
It won me a round or two.

48:31.950 --> 48:35.037
Ooh, thank you.

48:37.414 --> 48:39.166
That's nice.

48:40.334 --> 48:43.503
♪

48:43.545 --> 48:44.671
Uh, that was amazing.

48:44.713 --> 48:46.506
[laughing]

48:46.548 --> 48:49.885
I'm glad my post-gradcame in handy for something.

48:49.927 --> 48:51.428
Thank you for sharing.

48:51.470 --> 48:52.596
Mmm.

48:52.638 --> 48:53.472
You're welcome.

48:53.472 --> 48:54.348
Sharing an estate is easy.

48:54.640 --> 48:57.726
Sharing my popcorn,that's a challenge.

48:57.768 --> 49:00.479
Well, I'd say we're doinga pretty good job at it.

49:00.479 --> 49:05.067
You know, we were alwaysdifferent.

49:05.108 --> 49:06.902
But somehow it just works.

49:06.943 --> 49:10.113
You know what they sayabout opposites.

49:10.155 --> 49:17.245
So uh, you and Hannahseem pretty close, huh?

49:17.287 --> 49:21.041
Sure. I mean, she's beenvery helpful with things.

49:21.083 --> 49:23.168
You sure it ends there?

49:23.210 --> 49:25.337
Yes, I am sure it ends there.

49:25.337 --> 49:28.382
[laughs]

49:28.423 --> 49:29.758
What about you?

49:29.800 --> 49:33.428
Are you, uh, are youseeing anyone back in London?

49:33.470 --> 49:34.972
No, not really.

49:35.013 --> 49:36.932
The last guy I datedwas perfectly nice

49:36.974 --> 49:39.226
but he just didn't appreciate

49:39.267 --> 49:42.980
the things I'm passionate about,you know?

49:43.021 --> 49:45.065
The final straw was whenI caught him listening

49:45.107 --> 49:49.528
to a cricket match ata Michelangelo exhibit.

49:49.528 --> 49:51.488
[thunder rolls]

49:51.530 --> 49:53.240
Woah.

49:53.281 --> 49:54.950
We should probably head back.

49:54.992 --> 49:57.244
Yeah, and I've got a conferencecall to prepare.

49:57.285 --> 50:00.038
Not to mention a GildedAge Ball to plan.

50:00.080 --> 50:02.249
Let's go.

50:03.291 --> 50:07.087
Brr, that came down fast!

50:07.129 --> 50:09.381
Let's get a fire started,warm this place up.

50:11.967 --> 50:13.552
It'll be a lot easier to fixthings up around here

50:13.593 --> 50:16.388
if our fingers aren'tfrozen solid.

50:16.430 --> 50:17.723
That's good.

50:17.723 --> 50:18.724
Hurry up.

50:18.765 --> 50:20.642
I'm trying.

50:20.684 --> 50:24.646
Get closer. I'm freezing.

50:24.688 --> 50:29.109
[phone rings]

50:29.151 --> 50:31.027
Work calls. Again.

50:31.069 --> 50:36.324
Alright, well I'll just be righthere trying to get this lit.

50:36.366 --> 50:37.409
Hi, Josephine.

50:37.451 --> 50:39.828
Lucy, how's the life of luxury?

50:39.870 --> 50:41.163
[laughs]

50:41.204 --> 50:42.122
Lovely.

50:42.414 --> 50:46.084
Just missing a few modernconveniences like heating.

50:46.084 --> 50:48.336
Can you hear myteeth chattering?

50:48.378 --> 50:49.296
And Duncan?

50:49.337 --> 50:50.881
Still a battle of wills?

50:50.922 --> 50:55.427
Actually, he's been a littlemore Gandhi than Genghis lately.

50:55.427 --> 50:56.428
Go figure.

50:56.720 --> 50:58.472
Well I just wanted to let youknow that I emailed you

50:58.513 --> 51:01.600
the spreadsheets you asked forwith all of the donor totals

51:01.600 --> 51:02.601
for your call.

51:02.601 --> 51:03.769
Perfect, thank you.

51:03.769 --> 51:05.270
And I'll give you a heads up

51:05.312 --> 51:07.397
when I know what time yourcall is with the trustees.

51:07.439 --> 51:09.608
In the meantime,stay warm.

51:09.649 --> 51:11.276
Bye, Josephine. Thank you.

51:11.276 --> 51:12.277
Bye.

51:12.319 --> 51:14.237
(Duncan): Finally!

51:19.242 --> 51:20.952
This is better.

51:20.994 --> 51:23.163
Everything okon the home front?

51:23.205 --> 51:26.291
Yeah. Just getting my ducks ina row for my conference call

51:26.291 --> 51:28.168
with the trustees.

51:28.210 --> 51:29.878
The big promotion.

51:29.920 --> 51:33.215
Mmmhmm.

51:33.256 --> 51:36.760
You really wantthis new job, huh?

51:36.802 --> 51:38.678
Of course I do.

51:38.720 --> 51:42.432
Then why don't you soundso convinced?

51:42.474 --> 51:48.522
It's just I got into museum workbecause I love history.

51:48.563 --> 51:49.689
Preserving the past.

